{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487089","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487089"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:56:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:56:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"250"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"250","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/250"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.69,0.12,0.12,0.03,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"250"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56285"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"250","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/250"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"250"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41840"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1106"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9656"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10260"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10490"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15576"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17341"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17395"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38450"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42039"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56285","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56285"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old man with a history of epilepsy is brought to the Emergency Department after experiencing a seizure at work. He arrives with reduced consciousness, profound confusion, and an inability to provide a clear medical history. During the clinical assessment, the patient has another tonic-clonic seizure. Promptly, he is placed on his left side, and the airway is secured. An intravenous cannula is inserted, and 10mg of midazolam is administered. Despite these interventions, the patient\u0027s seizure continues. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Administer a repeat dose of midazolam (10mg)","Initiate a loading dose of phenytoin","Administer intravenous levetiracetam","Consider intramuscular lorazepam administration","Prepare for endotracheal intubation and mechanical ventilation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EStatus epilepticus is defined as continuous seizure activity for more than 5 minutes or recurrent seizures without a period of neurological recovery. In this case, the patient experiences a second seizure event while still recovering from the first, immediately classifying him as being in status epilepticus. The primary goal of treatment is to control the seizure before neuronal injury occurs, theoretically happening between 20 minutes to 1 hour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrompt and appropriate management is crucial. This includes inserting an airway adjunct if safe, administering oxygen, placing the patient in a semi-prone position with the head down, establishing IV access, and obtaining blood glucose levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe first-line drug treatment should be initiated within 5 to 15 minutes, using benzodiazepine drug therapy. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor patients with IV access, 10mg of IV midazolam is recommended. If the seizure persists or recure, a \u003Cstrong\u003Esecond dose of IV midazolam can be administered\u003C/strong\u003E. In cases where venous access is challenging, intramuscular midazolam administration is a viable alternative. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELorazepam\u003C/strong\u003E is another benzodiazepine which can be used in status epilepticus, however it should be administered intravenously, and not intramuscular. Current recommendations also rank midazolam, diazepam, and clonazepam as more preferred options, in that order.   \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf seizures continue beyond 15 minutes, second-line drug treatment with \u003Cstrong\u003Ephenytoin\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Evalproate\u003C/strong\u003E should be initiated. If seizures persist despite second-line therapy, the patient is considered to have refractory status epilepticus, necessitating the initiation of IV anaesthetic agents, \u003Cstrong\u003Eendotracheal intubation, and mechanical ventilation.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Status epilepticus is defines as continuous seizure activity for greater than 5 minutes or recurrent seizures without an intervening period of neurological recovery.","The first-line management in patients (both adults and children) with status epilepticus is an intramuscular or intravenous benzodiazepine."],"references":["Betjemann JP, Lowenstein DH. Status epilepticus in adults. Lancet Neurol 2015; 14:615-24.","Glauser, T, Shinnar, S, Gloss, D, et al. Evidence-Based Guideline: Treatment of Convulsive Status Epilepticus in Children and Adults: Report of the Guideline Committee of the American Epilepsy Society.\u00a0Epilepsy currents, 2016; 16:48-61.","Smith R, Brown J. Midazolam for status epilepticus. Aust Prescr. 2017 Feb;40(1):23-25. doi: 10.18773/austprescr.2017.005. Epub 2017 Feb 1. PMID: 28246432; PMCID: PMC5313252.","Emergency Care Institute - Agency for Clinical Innovation. Seizure Medications. NSW Health. N.d. Available from: https://aci.health.nsw.gov.au/networks/eci/clinical/clinical-tools/neurology/seizures/seizure-medications"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41840"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"250"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41840","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41840"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-19T22:54:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-19T22:55:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"250"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56285"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"